load-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig05a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig05b.jpeg" height="1280" width="786" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig05b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig06a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1169" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig06a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig06b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1126" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig06b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig07.jpeg" height="1000" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig07" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span> Axial oblique two-dimensional SSFP image in a 20-year-old woman with partial anomalous pulmonary venous connections (right pulmonary veins <i>[RPV]</i> to the right atrium) and an intact atrial septum, status post repair. The right pulmonary veins were baffled through a surgically created atrial septal defect to the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig07">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig08a.jpeg" height="1280" width="863" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig08a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig08b.jpeg" height="1280" width="873" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig08b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig08c.jpeg" height="1280" width="779" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig08c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig09.jpeg" height="1280" width="882" aria-labelledby="fig09" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> D-TGA with VSD and pulmonary stenosis in a 17-month-old boy, status post Rastelli procedure and subsequent resection of subaortic stenosis and conduit replacement. Volume-rendered image from contrast material–enhanced MR angiography demonstrates a large pseudoaneurysm (arrow). The conduit has been removed from this image to better demonstrate the LV outflow tract and pseudoaneurysm. <i>Ao</i> = aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig09">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig10a.jpeg" height="1272" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig10b.jpeg" height="771" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig11a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1264" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig11b.jpeg" height="998" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig12.jpeg" height="1280" width="508" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> CCTGA, VSD, and pulmonary stenosis in a 20-year-old man, status post VSD closure and LV-to–pulmonary artery conduit. Two-dimensional SSFP images in the axial plane, arranged from inferior to superior (top to bottom), show that the conduit (arrow) arises from the right-sided, morphologic LV and inserts near the pulmonary artery bifurcation. Note the patent native pulmonary valve (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig13.jpeg" height="1280" width="1234" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span> Sagittal oblique proton-density–weighted turbo spin-echo image through the RV outflow tract in a 27-year-old woman with tetralogy of Fallot and pulmonary atresia, status post repair with RV-to–pulmonary artery conduit, with conduit stenosis at the level of the valve (*). This obstruction was relieved by placement of a transcatheter pulmonary valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig14a.jpeg" height="1280" width="962" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig14b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1188" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig15.jpeg" height="1280" width="1112" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Three-dimensional reconstruction from contrast material–enhanced MR angiography demonstrates a large venovenous collateral (*) draining into a left pulmonary vein <i>(PV)</i> in a patient status post Fontan procedure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig16a.jpeg" height="1280" width="622" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.323115096/asset/images/115096fig16b.jpeg" height="1280" width="663" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.323115096&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Marelli AJ, Mackie AS, Ionescu-Ittu R, Rahme E, Pilote L. Congenital heart disease in the general population: changing prevalence and age distribution. <em>Circulation</em> 2007;115(2):163–172.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.106.627224">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17210844/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Congenital+heart+disease+in+the+general+population%3A+changing+prevalence+and+age+distribution&amp;author=AJ+Marelli&amp;author=AS+Mackie&amp;author=R+Ionescu-Ittu&amp;author=E+Rahme&amp;author=L+Pilote&amp;publication_year=2007&amp;journal=Circulation&amp;pages=163-172&amp;doi=10.1161%2FCIRCULATIONAHA.106.627224&amp;pmid=17210844">Googl